              <span id="reviewTextContainer3397061545" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9388422681935133406">This would be funny if it weren&apos;t so bad. <br/><br/><br/><i>The Wrath and the Dawn</i> sells itself as a diverse, feminist retelling of Arabian Nights, and you know I&apos;m practically married to feminist novels. Spoiler alert: this was not feminist. Or diverse. Or even a good retelling of Arabian Nights. <br/><br/><br/>Shahrzad (I&apos;m going to call her Shazi from now on, because I can&apos;t spell) has one desire--she wants revenge on her best friend&apos;s murderer. Unfortunately, this killer happens to be a caliph who is rather fond of killing </span>
  <span id="freeText9388422681935133406" style="display:none">This would be funny if it weren't so bad. <br /><br /><br /><i>The Wrath and the Dawn</i> sells itself as a diverse, feminist retelling of Arabian Nights, and you know I'm practically married to feminist novels. Spoiler alert: this was not feminist. Or diverse. Or even a good retelling of Arabian Nights. <br /><br /><br />Shahrzad (I'm going to call her Shazi from now on, because I can't spell) has one desire--she wants revenge on her best friend's murderer. Unfortunately, this killer happens to be a caliph who is rather fond of killing his wives. She volunteers to marry him so killing him will be easier. And then... what do you know, she falls in love with him. That is not a joke. That's the actual plot. <br /><br /><br />Shazi tells Khalid, the caliph, a story each night, hoping to keep him from killing her. This would be okay, if she weren't such a horrible storyteller. She retold Aladdin, changing the name of the characters and... not much else. No suspense. No interest on my part. And yet the caliph is ✨fascinated.✨ <br /><br /><br />The setting is supposed to be based on ancient Persia, but you know what I got? A bunch of random foreign terms thrown in without any context or explanation as to what they mean. I didn't exactly want to be flipping to a glossary every time I saw a word I didn't know, so I ignored them after a while. This is not good worldbuilding. This is a failed attempt at adding diversity. <i>The Wrath and the Dawn</i> could easily take place in Europe, for all the actual diversity it incorporated. <br /><br /><br />At least the plot sounds promising, yes? Wrong. <br /><br /><br />Shazi is all talk and no action. She goes on these long inner monologues about how she's going to avenge her best friend's death and kill Khalid, and then she sees him and she's like... <br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>The fluttering in her stomach returned with a vengeance.</i>
</blockquote> <br /><br />For contrast, here's Shazi <i>before</i> she sees Khalid's ✨beautiful eyes.✨<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>I will live to see tomorrow's sunset. Make no mistake. I swear I will live to see as many sunsets as it takes. And I will kill you. With my own hands.</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />Not only is the concept ridiculous, the way it's executed is just as bad. There's something wrong with the pacing of this novel. I can't quite put my finger on it. It's rushed in places and glosses over the actual plot with flowery prose and promises of vengeance. <br /><br /><br />Speaking of flowery prose, we have this writing. *gags* I've never seen so much needless description in my life. Every single random person is described in intricate detail, from the exact color of their hair to the jewels on their clothing. I don't care about Shazi's turquoise mantle that's the exact color of the sea. I don't care about the gleam of Khalid's eyes. Get to the plot, please.<br /><br /><br />Anyway. That was horrible. <br /><br /><br />DNF. Believe it or not, I have better things to do with my life.<br />0.5 stars</span>
  <a data-text-id="9388422681935133406" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


